'''Biological globalization''' has been defined as "the spread of plants domesticated in one area to favorable environments around the world".<ref name=oxford>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Economic History: Human capital - Mongolia. Vol. 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ssNMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA536|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-510507-0|page=536}}</ref> [[Columbian Exchange]] is a classic example of biological globalization.<ref name=oxford/> A growing and changing human population plays an important part on what plants are moved to new locations and which are left untouched.<ref name="ncbi.nlm.nih.gov">{{cite web|last1=Forcina|first1=Giovanni|last2=Guerrini|first2=Monica|last3=van Grouw|first3=Hein|last4=Gupta|first4=Brij K.|last5=Panayides|first5=Panicos|last6=Hadjigerou|first6=Pantelis|last7=Al-Sheikhly|first7=Omar F.|last8=Awan|first8=Muhammad N.|last9=Khan|first9=Aleem A.|last10=Zeder|first10=Melinda A.|last11=Barbanera|first11=Filippo|title=Impacts of biological globalization in the Mediterranean: Unveiling the deep history of human-mediated gamebird dispersal|pmc=4371972|website=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|pages=3296–3301|doi=10.1073/pnas.1500677112|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> Early signs of biological globalization can be traced back to the mid 1860s.<ref name="Social Science Research Network">{{cite web|last1=Olmstead|first1=Alan L.|last2=Rhode|first2=Paul W.|title=Biological Globalization: The Other Grain Invasion|ssrn=932056|language=en|date=1 May 2006}}</ref> [[Wheat]] is an example of biological globalization that appeared early in the developmental timeline.<ref name="Social Science Research Network"/> Global trading was the beginning of biological globalization which integrated plants to new environments.<ref name="ncbi.nlm.nih.gov"/> The [[black francolin]] is another example as it was originally from the Mediterranean but is now a common eastern gamebird.<ref name="ncbi.nlm.nih.gov"/>

