[[Image:MonthlyUraniumSpot.png|thumb|right|350px|Monthly uranium spot price in USD per pound from 1980 to 2011. The 2007 price peak is clearly visible.<ref name=uraniumingo>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uranium.info/prices/monthly.html |title=NUEXCO Exchange Value (Monthly Uranium Spot) |access-date=2010-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212170510/http://www.uranium.info/prices/monthly.html |archive-date=2007-12-12 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>]]
The '''uranium bubble of 2007''' was a period of nearly [[exponential growth]] in the price of natural uranium, starting in 2005<ref name="goldseek">{{Cite web |url=http://news.goldseek.com/TonyLocantro/1121781600.php |title=Uranium Bubble & Spec Market Outlook |date=2005-06-19 |accessdate=2009-11-23 |publisher=GoldSeek |author=Tony Locantro }}</ref> and peaking at roughly $300/kg (or ~$135/lb) in mid-2007.<ref name="bubble">{{Cite web |url=http://randomroger.blogspot.com/2007/02/uranium-bubble.html |title=Uranium a Bubble? |date=2007-02-20 |accessdate=2009-11-23 }}</ref> This coincided with significant rises of stock price of uranium mining and exploration companies.<ref name="bottom">{{Cite web |url=http://www.uraniumseek.com/news/UraniumSeek/1219431716.php |title=Uranium Has Bottomed: Two Uranium Bulls to Jump on Now |author=Andrew Mickey |date=2008-08-22 |publisher=UraniumSeek.com |accessdate=2009-11-23}}</ref> After mid-2007, the price began to fall again and at the end of 2010, was relatively stable at around $100/kg.<ref name="chart">{{Cite web |url=http://www.infomine.com/investment/charts.aspx?mv=1&f=f&r=10y&c=curanium.xusd.ukg#chart |title=Dynamic Charting Tool - 10 year uranium price in US$/kg |accessdate=2009-11-23 |publisher=InvestmentMine}}</ref>
==Causes== The upward trend for the prices of [[uranium]] was already apparent since 2003. This prompted increases in mining activity. A possible direct cause for the bubble is the flooding of the [[Cigar Lake Mine]], [[Saskatchewan]], which has the largest undeveloped high-grade uranium ore deposits in the world. This created uncertainty about short-term future of the uranium supply.<ref name="bottom"/> Other factors are speculation triggered by growing expectations around [[Nuclear power in India|India]] and [[Nuclear power in the People's Republic of China|China]]'s nuclear programs, and a reduction in available [[Megatons to Megawatts Program|weapons-grade uranium]].<ref>http://www.cfr.org/energy/global-uranium-supply-demand/p14705</ref>
==Impact== The impact of the bubble on [[nuclear power]] generation was small, as most power plants have long-term uranium delivery contracts,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cameco.com/uranium_101/markets/ |title=Uranium 101: Markets |publisher=Cameco }}</ref> and the price of natural uranium makes up only a small fraction of their operating cost. However, the sharp fall in prices after mid-2007 caused a lot of new companies focused on exploration and mining to lose their viability and go out of business.<ref name="bottom"/> Due to increased prospecting, known and inferred reserves of uranium have increased by 15% between 2005 and 2007.<ref name="wnachart">{{Cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf75.html |title=Supply of Uranium |publisher=World Nuclear Association |date=August 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-23 }}</ref>
==See also== * [[2000s commodities boom]] * [[Uranium Participation Corporation]]
